# stream-csv-as-json — AI Agent Rules

## Project identity

stream-csv-as-json is a micro-library of Node.js stream components for creating custom CSV processing pipelines with a minimal memory footprint. It can parse CSV files far exceeding available memory streaming individual primitives using a SAX-inspired API. The npm package name is `stream-csv-as-json`. It depends on `stream-json` for token infrastructure and `stream-chain` for pipeline composition.

## Critical rules

- **CommonJS.** `"type": "commonjs"` in package.json. Source uses `require()`. Tests use ESM/CJS/TS.
- **No transpilation.** Code runs directly.
- **One runtime dependency: `stream-json`.** Do not add other packages to `dependencies`. Only `devDependencies` are allowed.
- **Do not modify or delete test expectations** without understanding why they changed.
- **Do not add comments or remove comments** unless explicitly asked.
- **Token-based architecture.** The parser produces `{name, value}` tokens compatible with `stream-json`'s token protocol. All components operate on this protocol.
- **Backpressure is handled by `stream-chain`.** Components are flushable functions composed via `gen()` and wrapped with `asStream()`.

## Code style

- Prettier: 160 char width, single quotes, no bracket spacing, no trailing commas, arrow parens "avoid" (see `.prettierrc`).
- 2-space indentation.
- Semicolons are enforced by Prettier (default `semi: true`).
- Each `.js` file has a `// @ts-self-types` header pointing to its `.d.ts`.

## Architecture quick reference

- **Parser** (`src/parser.js`) consumes CSV text, produces SAX-like token stream. Factory: `parser(options)` / `parser.asStream(options)`.
  - Options: `packStrings`/`packValues`, `streamStrings`/`streamValues`, `separator`.
- **AsObjects** (`src/as-objects.js`) uses the first row as field names, converts subsequent rows from array tokens to object tokens.
  - Options: `packKeys`, `streamKeys`, `useStringValues`/`useValues`, `fieldPrefix`.
  - `.withParser(options)` / `.withParserAsStream(options)` for pipeline creation.
- **Stringer** (`src/stringer.js`) converts CSV token stream back to CSV text. Handles quoting.
  - Options: `useStringValues`/`useValues`, `separator`.
- **Main module** (`src/index.js`) creates a Parser Duplex with `emit()` applied (from `stream-json/utils/emit`).
- **with-parser** (`src/utils/with-parser.js`) CSV-specific withParser utility.

## Verification commands

- `npm test` — run the full test suite (tape-six)
- `npm run ts-check` — TypeScript type checking
- `npm run lint` / `npm run lint:fix` — Prettier

## File layout

- Source: `src/` — `index.js`, `parser.js`, `as-objects.js`, `stringer.js`, `utils/with-parser.js` (each with `.d.ts`)
- Tests: `tests/test-*.mjs` (ESM), `test-*.cjs` (CJS), `test-*.mts` (TS) — tape-six
- Wiki docs: `wiki/` (git submodule)

## When reading the codebase

- Start with `ARCHITECTURE.md` for the module map and dependency graph.
- `src/parser.js` is the core — read it first to understand the CSV token protocol.
- `src/as-objects.js` converts array-of-strings rows into object token streams.
- `src/stringer.js` does the inverse: token stream back to CSV text.
- Wiki markdown files in `wiki/` contain detailed usage docs.
